\f1\b \cf0 The Nominative and Accusative Cases\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 The nominative and accusative cases are used to express the 
\f1\b subject
\f0\b0  and 
\f1\b object
\f0\b0  respectively of finite verbs.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Examples:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f4 \cf0 \uc0\u2310 \u2330 \u2366 \u2352 \u2381 \u2351 \u2307 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2358 \u2367 \u2359 \u2381 \u2351 \u2306 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2346 \u2358 \u2381 \u2351 \u2340 \u2367 
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 \u257 c\u257 rya\u7717  \u347 i\u7779 yam pa\u347 yati 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  "The teacher sees the pupil.\'94\'f9\

\f4\b \uc0\u2310 \u2330 \u2366 \u2352 \u2381 \u2351 \u2306 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2358 \u2367 \u2359 \u2381 \u2351 \u2307 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2346 \u2358 \u2381 \u2351 \u2340 \u2367 
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 \u257 c\u257 ryam \u347 i\u7779 ya\u7717  pa\u347 yati 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  "The pupil sees the teacher."\
There is no 
\f1\b definite or indefinite article
\f0\b0  in Sanskrit. In one context, 
\f3\i \uc0\u257 c\u257 rya\u7717 
\f0\i0  can mean "the teacher," and in another, "a teacher."\uc0\u8232 (Where the difference of meaning is crucial, 
\f3\i 'the'
\f0\i0  is sometimes represented by 
\f4\b \uc0\u2360 \u2307 
\f0\b0  (
\f3\i sa\uc0\u7717 
\f0\i0 ) meaning 
\f3\i 'that'
\f0\i0 .)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Example for Demonstratives:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f4 \cf0 \uc0\u2330 \u2367 \u2340 \u2381 \u2352 \u2350 \u2375 \u2340 \u2340 \u2381 
\f0\b0  (
\f3\i citram etat
\f0\i0 ) 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  "This is a picture."\uc0\u8232 
\f4\b \uc0\u2340 \u2340 \u2381 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2319 \u2340 \u2340 \u2381 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2330 \u2367 \u2340 \u2381 \u2352 \u2350 \u2381 
\f0\b0  (
\f3\i tat etat citram
\f0\i0 ) 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  "This is the picture."\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Accusative with Verbs of Motion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 The accusative case is also used to express the 
\f1\b goal
\f0\b0  with verbs of motion:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf0 \uc0\u2344 \u2327 \u2352 \u2306 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2327 \u2330 \u2381 \u2331 \u2340 \u2367 
\f0\b0  (
\f3\i nagaram gacchati
\f0\i0 ) 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  "He goes to the city."\
Verbs such as 
\f1\b n\uc0\u299 
\f0\b0  ("lead") may take this accusative in addition to that of the direct object:\

\f4\b \uc0\u2344 \u2327 \u2352 \u2306 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2340 \u2381 \u2357 \u2366 \u2306 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2344 \u2351 \u2366 \u2350 \u2367 
\f0\b0  (
\f3\i nagaram tv\uc0\u257 m nay\u257 mi
\f0\i0 ) 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  "I\'92ll take you to the city."\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Accusative with 'Say' and Optional Pronoun Use\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 The verb 
\f1\b vad
\f0\b0  ("say, speak") may optionally take an 
\f1\b accusative
\f0\b0  of the person addressed as well as an 
\f1\b accusative
\f0\b0  of what is said.\
As seen in Chapter 2, 
\f1\b finite verb forms distinguish person and number.
\f0\b0  Because of this, the use of nominative personal pronouns is usually optional unless emphasis is needed:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf0 \uc0\u2346 \u2381 \u2352 \u2357 \u2367 \u2360 \u2366 \u2350 \u2367 
\f0\b0  (
\f3\i pravi\uc0\u347 \u257 mi
\f0\i0 ) 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  "I\'92ll go in."\uc0\u8232 
\f4\b \uc0\u2309 \u2361 \u2350 \u2346 \u2367 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2346 \u2381 \u2352 \u2357 \u2367 \u2360 \u2366 \u2350 \u2367 
\f0\b0  (
\f3\i aham api pravi\uc0\u347 \u257 mi
\f0\i0 ) 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  "I 
\f3\i too
\f0\i0  will go in."\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 The Vocative Case\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 The 
\f1\b vocative case
\f0\b0  is used for 
\f1\b addressing
\f0\b0  someone. It is usually placed at the 
\f1\b beginning
\f0\b0  of the sentence and often precedes even connecting particles.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf0 \uc0\u2348 \u2366 \u2354 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2325 \u2367 \u2306 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2357 \u2342 \u2360 \u2367 
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f1\b b\uc0\u257 la ki\u7745  vadasi
\f0\b0  
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  "What do you say, child?"\

\f4\b \uc0\u2357 \u2351 \u2360 \u2381 \u2351 
\f1 , 
\f4 \uc0\u2340 \u2340 \u2381 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2325 \u2367 \u2306 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2358 \u2379 \u2330 \u2360 \u2367 
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f1\b vayasya, tat ki\uc0\u7745  \u347 ocasi?
\f0\b0  
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  "Then why, friend, do you grieve?"\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 In a phrase such as 
\f3\i \'91the large cat\'92
\f0\i0 , we often call 
\f3\i \'91large\'92
\f0\i0  an adjective and 
\f3\i \'91cat\'92
\f0\i0  a noun. More formally, both might be called nouns: 
\f3\i \'91large\'92
\f0\i0  a noun adjective and 
\f3\i \'91cat\'92
\f0\i0  a noun substantive. To preserve this wider sense of the word 
\f3\i \'91noun\'92
\f0\i0  in talking about Sanskrit is not mere pedantry, for many nouns may be used both adjectivally and substantivally, and the classification of nouns by inflexional type is independent of whether they are substantives or adjectives. In this book, the terms 
\f3\i \'91noun\'92
\f0\i0  and 
\f3\i \'91nominal\'92
\f0\i0  are to be interpreted in their wider sense.\
Adjectives ending in 
\f1\b a
\f0\b0  inflect in the 
\f1\b masculine
\f0\b0  like 
\f3\i a\uc0\u347 va\u7717 
\f0\i0 , in the 
\f1\b neuter
\f0\b0  like 
\f3\i phalam
\f0\i0 . An adjective accords in 
\f1\b number, gender,
\f0\b0  and 
\f1\b case
\f0\b0  with the substantive it qualifies:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf0 \uc0\u2352 \u2350 \u2339 \u2368 \u2351 \u2366 \u2344 \u2367 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2357 \u2344 \u2366 \u2344 \u2367 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2358 \u2379 \u2349 \u2344 \u2306 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2332 \u2354 \u2306 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2330 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2346 \u2358 \u2381 \u2351 \u2366 \u2350 \u2367 
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f1\b rama\uc0\u7751 \u299 y\u257 ni van\u257 ni \u347 obhana\u7745  jala\u7745  ca pa\u347 y\u257 mi
\f0\b0  
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  "I see pleasant forests and shining water."\
Pronouns, no less than nouns, may be used both 
