\f1\b \cf0 Nominal sentences\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 There is an important type of sentence in Sanskrit which contains no verb. Such sentences, consisting of a juxtaposition of subject and non-verbal predicate, are a feature of many Indo-European languages. In English the type is almost lost, and when used it has a literary flavour, as in \'91happy the man who\'85\'92. In Greek there are sentences like 
\f3\i soph\'f3s ho phil\'f3sophos
\f0\i0  \'91the philosopher is wise\'92; in a song of Edith Piaf occurs 
\f3\i balay\'e9es les amours
\f0\i0  \'91loves are swept away\'92. Regularly in such an English sentence the subject is 
\f3\i not
\f0\i0  placed first. A twentieth-century poet, T. S. Eliot, can write \'91dark the Sun and Moon, and the Almanach de Gotha\'92, but \'91the Sun and Moon dark\'92 would hardly have been possible. This fact distinguishes such a sentence from one simply involving an ellipse of the verb \'91to be\'92: we 
\f3\i may
\f0\i0  say \'91John is intelligent, Peter stupid\'92.\
In Sanskrit adjectives used predicatively agree in number, gender and case with their substantive, just as when used attributively. As a phrase, 
\f4\b \uc0\u2358 \u2368 \u2328 \u2381 \u2352 \u2380 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2309 \u2358 \u2381 \u2357 \u2380 
\f0\b0  
\f3\i \uc0\u347 \u299 ghrau a\u347 vau
\f0\i0  means \'91the two swift horses\'92; as a complete statement, it means \'91the two horses are swift\'92.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf0 \uc0\u2352 \u2350 \u2339 \u2368 \u2351 \u2307 
