\f0\i0 , etc). In this chapter attention is confined to one class of compounds, co-ordinatives, which from the point of view of English are the most peculiar (we may find a faint echo of them in a word such as 
\f3\i bitter-sweet
\f0\i0  or the compound numerals such as 
\f3\i sixty-seven
\f0\i0 ).\
In English we may wonder whether a phrase such as 
\f3\i magazine stand
\f0\i0  should be classified as a compound at all. In Sanskrit there is a simple criterion which is almost universally valid. All members of a compound except the last appear in their stem form. The stem form of a noun is the form lacking any case termination. 
\f3\i a\uc0\u347 va
\f0\i0 , 
\f3\i phala
\f0\i0  and 
\f3\i raman\uc0\u299 ya
\f0\i0  are stem forms. Nouns are usually quoted in their stem forms in dictionaries; when quoted in this book, however, substantives in 
\f3\i a
\f0\i0  usually have visarga or anusv\uc0\u257 ra added to them as an aid to remembering whether they are masculine or neuter.\
To form a co-ordinative compound (called in Sanskrit 
\f2 \uc0\u2342 \u2381 \u2357 \u2344 \u2381 \u2342 \u2381 \u2357 
\f3\i  dvandva
\f0\i0  'couple') two or more stems are put together with a relationship between them such as would be expressed by the English word 'and':\

\f4\b \uc0\u2310 \u2330 \u2366 \u2352 \u2381 \u2351 \u2358 \u2367 \u2359 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f1\b \uc0\u257 c\u257 rya\u347 i\u7779 ya
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 'teacher and pupil'.\
The compound is that of its final member, and the number is that of the sum of the elements; an appropriate inflexion is added:\

\f4\b \uc0\u2310 \u2330 \u2366 \u2352 \u2381 \u2351 \u2358 \u2367 \u2359 \u2381 \u2351 \u2380 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2310 \u2327 \u2330 \u2381 \u2331 \u2340 \u2307 
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f1\b \uc0\u257 c\u257 rya\u347 i\u7779 yau \u257 gacchata\u7717 
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 teacher and pupil are coming\
The same notion may, of course, be expressed without the use of a compound, by means of the particle 
\f3\i ca
\f0\i0 :\

\f4\b \uc0\u2310 \u2330 \u2366 \u2352 \u2381 \u2351 \u2307 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2358 \u2367 \u2359 \u2381 \u2351 \u2307 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2330 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2310 \u2327 \u2330 \u2381 \u2331 \u2340 \u2307 
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f1\b \uc0\u257 c\u257 rya\u7717  ca \u347 i\u7779 ya\u7717  ca \u257 gacchata\u7717 
\f0\b0 \
Stem forms are ambiguous as between singular, dual and plural. 
\f3\i \uc0\u257 c\u257 rya\u347 i\u7779 ya
\f0\i0  may therefore also mean \'91teachers and pupils\'92, \'91teacher and pupils\'92 or \'91teachers and pupil\'92. In all these instances the inflexions are inevitably plural (signifying three or more).\
Any number of stems may be put together in a 
\f3\i dvandva
\f0\i0 . Again, if more than two stems are involved, the final inflexion must necessarily be plural:\

\f4\b \uc0\u2309 \u2358 \u2381 \u2357 \u2327 \u2332 \u2348 \u2366 \u2354 \u2344 \u2352 \u2366 \u2307 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2344 \u2371 \u2340 \u2381 \u2351 \u2344 \u2381 \u2340 \u2367 
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f1\b a\uc0\u347 va; gaja; b\u257 la; nar\u257 \u7717  n\u7771 tyanti
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 horses, elephants, children and men are dancing\
